# Coding Standards

## Readability

- Use clear, descriptive variable names that communicate intent — never abbreviate unless universally understood (`url`, `id`, `html`)
- Never use destructuring assignment
- Never use the spread operator (`...`) — copy properties explicitly or use `Object.assign` / `Array.prototype.concat`

```ts
// ❌ BAD
const { name, type } = microbe;
const merged = { ...defaults, ...overrides };
const copy = [...items, newItem];

// ✅ GOOD
const name = microbe.name;
const type = microbe.type;
const merged = Object.assign({}, defaults, overrides);
const copy = items.concat([newItem]);
```

## Error Handling

- Always wrap async operations and anything that can throw in a `try/catch`
- Log errors in this exact format:

```
[functionName] || [what you were trying to do] || [error message] || 🐧
```

Pick a **random animal emoji** each time — never reuse the same one twice in a file.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
async function getMicrobe(id: string) {
  const microbe = await db.find(id);
  return microbe;
}

// ✅ GOOD
async function getMicrobe(id: string) {
  try {
    const microbe = await db.find(id);
    return microbe;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(`getMicrobe || fetching microbe by id ${id} || ${error.message} || 🦦`);
    throw error;
  }
}
```

## JSDoc

- Every function — including React components, helpers, and service methods — must have a JSDoc comment
- Document parameters, return type, and a one-line summary

```ts
/**
 * Fetches a single microbe record from the database by its ID.
 * @param id - The unique identifier of the microbe
 * @returns The microbe entity, or null if not found
 */
async function getMicrobe(id: string): Promise<Microbe | null> { ... }
```

